ury Spanish culture, while probing issues that are still seen as defining of Spanish identity today. Artículos de costumbres, presented here with an extensive annotation that identifies references that have not been previously elucidated, is a central text in the Spanish canon, opening up questions about modern Spain and issues such as political revolution, class identities, social change and the inclusion of Spain within European modernity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSpanish literaturey19th century. 7aREFERENCE / Etiquette.2bisacsh  aCostumbrismo.  aJournalism.  aMariano José de Larra.  aSatire.  aSpanish Romanticism.1 aMuñoz Sempere, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMuñoz Sempere, Daniel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152612220940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526122209423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526122209/original  a978-3-11-128281-7  Manchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packageb2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles